body: Is onnxruntime built from source or using a release binary package?

*ONNX Runtime version: 1.2 native* is very old. Are you sure it is 1.2?

Have you tried with the latest ort package? One possible reason is the ort binary you are using was not built with the compute capability applicable to your GPU because of which jit compilation actually takes place during CUDA initialization and hence the long latency. Having said that 20 mins is still very high. I would except the session initialization latency to be ~60 secs due to jit compilation as opposed to 1-2 secs. 

You can run 
```
 cuobjdump -sass libonnxruntime_providers_cuda.so  | grep "arch ="
```
and check whether ort binary includes the right sm_arch applicable to your gpu. If it does then we can rule out jit compilation.

sm_86 is what's required for the new rtx4000,6000's, and I don't believe onnxruntime is built with that architecture enabled by default.
if one builds from source, you can add support for a specific cuda arch via CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES
i.e. add this build option to the build.bat command 
--cmake_extra_defines CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES=86

@jywu-msft: But we build with sm_80 right ? Shouldn't this binary code be useable in CC 8.6 cards because of Nvidia's one minor revision binary compatibility guarantee (https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-c-programming-guide/index.html#binary-compatibility) ? Or is my understanding of this incorrect ?

> @jywu-msft: But we build with sm_80 right ? Shouldn't this binary code be useable in CC 8.6 cards because of Nvidia's one minor revision binary compatibility guarantee (https://docs.nvidia.com/cuda/cuda-c-programming-guide/index.html#binary-compatibility) ? Or is my understanding of this incorrect ?

I should have written that sm_86 is what's optimal for rtx4000's (instead of writing required)
kernels compiled with 80 support should still work on 86 hardware as you mentioned.
but here, it's not clear what version of ORT is being used here and what arch the kernels are compiled for.

Thanks all for the reply.  We do not build onnxruntime.dll, just take from the package and use it in our product on the trained CNN Model.   Our released product runs on Cuda 10.1, onnxruntime v1.10, cudnn v7 combination which apparently does not work well with the newer NVIDIA RTX cards.  I am testing a higher set of library combination according to the chart in tis link https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/execution-providers/CUDA-ExecutionProvider.html#gpu_mem_limit.  Hope the higher combination will solve the RTX issue.  Also I will need to understand what is the appropriate sm and compute numbers to set that will work for a wide ranges of GPU cards, ours is set to sm_50, compute_50 is it OK?  I  am also worry of the higher combination will drop the support of lower/older version of GPU cards and cause complaint from the other end.

Can you confirm whether you're using onnxruntime 1.1.0 or 1.10.0 (1.10.0 was released just a few days ago)
I ask because you refer to CUDA 10.1, which is a very old version. 
The 1.10.0 release packages depend on CUDA 11.x

> Can you confirm whether you're using onnxruntime 1.1.0 or 1.10.0 (1.10.0 was released just a few days ago) I ask because you refer to CUDA 10.1, which is a very old version. The 1.10.0 release packages depend on CUDA 11.x
You are right, the onnxruntime version in our release is the old 1.1.0 which works with CUDA 10.1.

Just finished a test environment with onnxruntime v 1.17,  Cuda v 11.0, Cudnn v8.02.39.  I am pleased that my unit test gives impressive time of 8 sec.  It looks the Cudnn version 8 is the one needed to support RTX GPU.   Besides cudnn64_8.dll, I also included cudnn_cnn_infer64_8.dll and cudnn_ops_infer64_8.dll  
In CUDA property, I set sm_50, compute_50.  Should I set a higher sm and compute value?  
THANKS.
you should set the cuda arch to what your gpu device(s) can support.
